%text The table below summarizes the strategy to use when one encounters integrals of the following forms % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{NN}
\hline \text{Integral} & \text{Convert to} \\ \hline \int \frac{dx}{\sqrt{ax^2+bx+c}}\cdot dx & \int \frac{dx}{\sqrt{\left(x + \alpha \right)^2 \pm \beta^2}}\\ \hline \int \frac{dx}{ax^2+bx+c}\cdot dx & \int \frac{dx}{\left(x + \alpha \right)^2 \pm \beta^2}\\ \hline \int\frac{ \left( px+q\right) \cdot dx}{\sqrt{ax^2+bx+c}} & \underbrace{ \int \frac{A f'(x) + B}{\sqrt{f(x)}}\cdot dx}_{f(x) = ax^2+bx+c}\\ \hline \int\frac{ \left( px+q\right) \cdot dx}{ax^2+bx+c} & \underbrace{ \int \frac{A f'(x) + B}{f(x)}\cdot dx}_{f(x) = ax^2+bx+c}\\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text So, these might be four different types of integrals. But they can be solved using jsut two strategies
- Completing the squares, that is, re-writing the \underline\text{denominator} $f(x) = ax^2+bx+c$ as $ \left(x+\alpha \right)^2 \pm \beta$ - Re-writing the \underline\text{numerator} as $Af'(x)+B$, where $f(x)$ is the denominator %
